<m1><styl>txt,14p<ql>
<ep>
<m0>   All American Semiconductor of Miami said it has received a $100 million credit line from a bank group led by American National Bank & Trust of Chicago and Harris Trust & Savings Bank.<ep>
   The five-year secured credit line replaces both the company's $45 million credit line and its $15 million in subordinated bank debt. The distributor of electronic components said the availability of a larger amount of capital will enhance its ability to expand.<ep>
<m1><styl>hed,14p,18,2,jam<ql>
<m0>French Fragrances<ql>
<m4>   LINE 1 IS 3.17 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m0>plans stock offering<ql>
<m1><ue5><m4>   LINE 2 IS 2.11 PICA(S) SHORT<m2><ql>
<m4>   TOTAL HEAD DEPTH IS .608 INCHES<m2><ql>
<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,14p<ql>
<ep>
<m0>  French Fragrances, a Miami Lakes-based perfume distributor, plans to sell 4.75 million shares of stock, according to a statement filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.<ep>
   The company plans to raise about $19 million through the sale of 3 million shares, said the statement filed Friday with the SEC. Existing investors including chief executive Rafael Kravec will sell another 1.75 million. Kravec will sell 475,000 shares, cutting his stake to 2.47 million shares, or 19.4 percent.<ep>
   French Fragrances plans to use its proceeds to repay at least $9.25 million of bank debt, according to the filing, and the rest for working capital and other expenses. The company sells perfumes through chains such as Sears and Wal-Mart.<ep>
